post_text:
Our last day for regular meal service is Wednesday, June 17. On Monday, June 22, we will move to our free summer meal service. We will continue to serve grab & go breakfast and lunch meals on Mondays and Wednesdays from 11 a.m.-12 p.m. at the locations listed below. Monday’s service will have meals for Monday and Tuesday, Wednesday’s service will provide meals for Wed-Fri. The summer program will run through August 21.

• Meals are free, no ID, no family income or prequalifications is required.
• Meals are “grab and go” intended to be taken off campus.
• Meals are available on Mondays and Wednesdays 11 a.m. – 12 p.m.
• Child does not need to be present to pick-up meals.
• Students/families can pick up meals at any school or location nearest them (you don’t have to go to your school).

See locations at www.rentonschools.us/students-families

Washington State has announced a program that provides families who are qualified for free/reduced lunch to receive up to an additional $399 on an Electronic Benefits Transfer (EBT) card. Because COVID-19 closed our schools, some children may be eligible for the additional food assistance, called Pandemic EBT (P-EBT): Emergency School Meals Program. Immigration status does not matter for P-EBT – it is not Basic Food and will not count in a public charge test.

If your family is not currently qualified for free/reduced meals, or does not receive Basic Food, and you’ve experienced a change in income or household size, you’re encouraged to apply to be considered for this program. Applications due by June 30, 2020.

Find the free/reduced lunch application at www.rentonschools.us/departments/nutrition-services-warehouse/meal-applications

For more information on the Pandemic EBT Emergency School Meals Program:
 Go to: https://www.washingtonconnection.org/home/, or
 Call DSHS at 877-501-2233

Renton School District is working to plan for the 2020-2021 school year. While guidance from the state education office has lots of caveats and leaves much to be worked through by local school districts, we want to hear from students and families about their in-home learning experiences over the past few months. Provide your input here: https://forms.gle/mUU5YuueMbZhCohd9 (Deadline for input is Tuesday, June 16.)

If you have students in different grade levels, you may choose to fill out the survey for each of those levels.

We will keep our community updated as we learn more and continue our planning efforts.

post_text:
In 1967, McKnight Middle School math teacher and boys basketball coach Cliff Donley was asked to leave a teacher celebration banquet hosted by Renton’s chapter of the Fraternal Order of the Eagles as that organization barred people of color. The organization discriminated against Donley who before becoming an educator served as a first lieutenant in the Korean War.

Sixty teachers stood in solidarity with Donley, and walked out of the event. Later, Donley and the Renton Education Association, the teachers union, filed a complaint against the organization with WA state, which was successful, resulting in the Eagles losing its liquor license for three weeks and forced to issue a formal apology.

The incident also launched a state-wide discussion in 1967 about whether organizations that hold a state liquor license could discriminate on the basis of race.

Mr. Donley, who in 1963 was only the second African American teacher hired in Renton, went on to become assistant principal at Hazen High School.

This story is shared by Renton History Museum https://m.facebook.com/rentonhistorymuseum/

Renton School Board members have recognized winners of the 2020 Outstanding Employee Awards.

The Board has presented the awards for nearly 40 years to recognize staff who demonstrate an extraordinary level of job performance, support of students, professionalism, and dedication. More than 160 teachers and support staff members were nominated for this year’s awards.

2020 Outstanding Employees:

• Outstanding Elementary Teacher: Kristyn Strauss, Hazelwood Elementary School

• Outstanding Secondary Teachers: Lance Winmil, Renton High School & Lisa Koenigsbergh-Roshon, Renton Academy

• Outstanding School Support Person: Luis Montes, Dimmitt Middle School

• Outstanding District Support Person: Monique Wise, Dept. of Learning & Teaching

Read more about these Outstanding Employees at www.rentonschools.us/our-district/school-board/school-board-outstanding-employee-awards

Renton educators were recently honored by Renton Chamber of Commerce at the annual Ahead of the Class awards held online during a live broadcast of Renton Live!

Ten teachers from Renton Schools and Renton Technical College, Renton Prep, and New Horizon schools are winners of Renton Chamber's 2020 Ahead of the Class awards:

• Sally Boni, Talbot Hill Elementary
• Amy Gross, McKnight Middle School
• Monica Herley, Campbell Hill Elementary
• Patti LaFleur, Bryn Mawr Elementary
• Lori McEwen, Talley High School
• Carla Smith, Hazen/Lindbergh/Renton High Schools
• Kiana Davis and Matt Edwards, Renton Technical College
• Tim Hines, New Horizon
• Emily Chant, Renton Prep

The Ahead of the Class award program is a partnership between the Renton Chamber of Commerce, Renton public and private schools and Renton businesses. The program’s aim is to enhance community awareness of excellence in education in Renton.

Watch a rebroadcast of the Chamber's event at www.facebook.com/rentonchamber/videos/968837756865931/

post_text:
Continuing to seize the opportunity as school playgrounds are off limits, Renton Schools is making improvements to elementary school playgrounds and replacing playground equipment. The work is made possible thanks to overwhelming voter support (70% approved!) in our Nov. 2019 school construction measure.‬ Those voter-approved funds, by law, can only be used for school construction, renovations, and upgrades. It cannot be used for instruction, classroom materials, teacher salaries, etc.

Additionally, thanks to the district’s solid financial management, excellent credit rating, and a favorable bond market, property owners in the district did not see an increase in school district tax rates even as they approved the important school construction measure. Click the link in the post to find out how https://bit.ly/2ZUq8TN

post_text: Renton School District’s fleet of school buses are safe and in top operating condition. That’s the finding of the Washington State Patrol’s recent summer inspection. Thanks to our mechanics, drivers, and the entire Transportation Department Team, 117 school buses and 22 district support vehicles were inspected and 100% passed. Inspectors focus on essential systems like mechanical, brakes, steering, and exhaust, as well as safety features like lights, stop paddles, tires, seats, emergency doors, and more. Washington State Patrol conducts two inspections each year: a planned inspection in the summer and a random surprise inspection in the winter.

Today is Memorial Day, a time to honor the men and women who have died while serving in the U.S. military.

Each year the City of Renton hosts a Memorial Day ceremony at Veterans Memorial Park, located at 523 S. 3rd St, downtown Renton. Due to the pandemic and guidelines for social distancing, in lieu of a ceremony, city staff will present a video tribute to veterans that can be viewed on their social media channels including their Facebook page: City of Renton, WA -- Government.

Veterans Memorial Park features five walls in the shape of a star representing the five different branches of the service. Engraved titles line the wall to commemorate the veterans.

Families are welcome to come pick-up free food items this Tuesday, May 19, 3:30-6 p.m. at Sunset Community Church, 1032 Edmonds Ave, NE in the Sunset neighborhood.

The food items are provided first come, first served. Everyone is welcome to pick-up food. No ID or qualifications needed. Families who drive thru are asked to stay in their vehicle; those who walk-up are asked to maintain social distancing.

Renton High School senior Ronald Lal is this year’s first graduate in the AJAC Production Technician Youth Apprenticeship program. Ronald began his apprenticeship program in 2018 and was immediately hired at Automatic Products in Kent. During his two-year apprenticeship, Ronald earned over 2,000 hours of paid on-the-job training, 15 tuition-free college credits, a nationally-recognized journeyman's certificate and lifelong mentorship from industry professionals.

The AJAC apprenticeship program helps teach high school students to work with tools and high-tech machinery, connects them with a company looking for highly-trained employees, and possibly a long-term career in aerospace and advanced manufacturing in Washington State. It’s one of the many ways Renton School District is helping students make good choices and be ready for many options after high school.

Learn more about the AJAC apprenticeship program at www.ajactraining.org/apprenticeship/

Families with 3- and 4-year-old children can start now to enroll in the district's Preschool, Head Start, and Early Childhood Education & Assistance Program (ECEAP) for the 2020-2021 school year.

Big News! We're adding a new, full-day Head Start preschool program at Campbell Hill Elementary School.

Head Start is a federally sponsored preschool program; ECEAP is a state sponsored preschool program. Families must meet income eligibility requirements to participate in these programs.

Our Inclusive Preschool program has two sessions per day Monday-Thursday, during the regular school year: 10 am-12:30 pm (AM session) or 1:30-4 pm (PM session). Tuition is $225/month. Transportation is not provided for this program.

Learn more and apply today at https://meadowcrest.rentonschools.us/programs/application

post_text:
A message of love and admiration from Renton High students to teachers & staff:

Dear RHS Staff,
We hope you are all doing well and taking care of yourselves and your loved ones! Although we believe that every week should be Teacher Appreciation Week, we wanted to celebrate you all today with a small gesture from our hearts. During this time filled with uncertainty, fear, and confusion, you have been our rocks and our support system throughout it all. We know you all do so much more behind the scenes than we ever get to see, but we want you to know that it never goes unnoticed or unappreciated. Whether we're seeing you in person in our classrooms or on a screen during a Zoom call, YOU all have always been the heart of Renton and we wouldn't be the students, athletes, or leaders we are today without you.
So from the bottom of our hearts, THANK YOU, and we agapé you ❤
Sincerely,
Alicia Ing, ASB President, and your 2019-2020 ASB Representatives

A Renton original, Robert W. McLendon, former president and CEO of McLendon’s Hardware and Renton High School graduate (class of 1942), recently passed away peacefully at his home in the district's Bryn Mawr neighborhood at the age of 96.

Bob's hard work and tenacity helped grow McLendon Hardware into one of the top ten independently owned hardware stores in the nation.

Read more about Bob in the Renton Reporter: https://www.rentonreporter.com/obituaries/obituary-robert-w-mclendon/

Hazen High School Principal Kate O'Brien joined several educational leaders in Washington state — all current students or alumni of the University of Washington Leadership for Learning (EdD) program — who recently shared their perspectives on some of the critical issues facing education leaders in Washington and beyond.

In a video podcast, Principal O'Brien and others discuss strategies they are pursuing to attend to the well-being of vulnerable students, what changes the COVID-19 crisis might prompt in school systems and more.

Read more and watch the podcast at https://education.uw.edu/news/education-leaders-share-perspectives-impact-covid-19?fbclid=IwAR2uCMQOPoBcSW5oX23HWDel-xgh-0u8VUWSyhXz4abD7XGpUGGRtydVifk

Hazen High School is ranked 37th in the state; Lindbergh High is 68th in the state.

To continue to support in-home learning, over the past two weeks Renton School District staff have provided 2,000 Chromebooks to families of elementary students. All students in grades 6-12 started this school year with a district-provided Chromebook to use at school and at home. Additionally, we’ve provided Wi-Fi hotspots to over 600 students, both before and during the closure. (Reminder: updated in-home learning materials are available on each school's website every Friday. Materials can be accessed with any computer or device.)

So, thanks to overwhelming voter support of the 2016 School Technology Levy, we’ve been able to provide 10,200 Chromebooks directly to students/families to support on-going education during this pandemic.

McKnight Middle School 7th graders recently worked to create persuasive videos about topics they’re passionate about. During a two-week remote learning mini-unit, students in Beth Laux and Kelly Lissak’s Language Arts classes learned how to:
• Evaluate the credibility of an online source
• Utilize research databases
• Research multiple perspectives before making their own claim
• Determine the rhetorical appeals most effective for their intended audience
• Defend their claims with researched evidence
• Identify and refute possible counterarguments
• Provide digital peer feedback using Flipgrid
• Craft a hook that interests the audience
• Create and edit a video using royalty-free media on WeVideo

Teachers and support staff are so proud of how hard students are working despite the physical closure of school buildings.

Here's one of the student's final work: Gretchen Freer – Should more women be in leadership roles? https://drive.google.com/file/d/1OBQ8NBknqDVXQosbq-4I4ne7gpurexva/view

post_text: Hazen High School’s business education teacher Peter Rustemeyer has been named Washington state’s Future Business Leader of America (FBLA) 2020 Adviser of the Year. Peter creates a strong and engaging curriculum to develop 21st Century skills needed by students to be ready to lead today’s workforce. His work is instrumental in helping students develop a passion, commitment, and willingness to continue to grow and learn. As an FBLA adviser, Peter treats students with kindness, discovers their passion, and empowers them with an opportunity to thrive and succeed in a meaningful organization. Peter also holds a position on the national FBLA Board of Directors and is a representative on the board of the Washington State Business Education Association. post_text: Newcastle resident (and drummer for the band Yes) worked with Newcastle Police Department to create a Public Service Announcement about the importance of social distancing. The video includes lyrics by Yes bassist Billy Sherwood.
shared_text:
YOUTUBE.COM
Don't Stand So Close To Me - A PSA From the Newcastle WA Police Department

Alan White
April 21 at 5:47 PM ·

Hey everyone!

I wanted to share this fun (but important) project that I was involved with recently. I was asked to help put together a PSA for the Newcastle Police Department about the importance of social distancing.

Newcastle's Police Chief, Jason Houck, penned a fresh set of lyrics to the classic Police (appropriate, right?) song "Don't Stand So Close To Me", and my wife Gigi and I contributed a few lyrical suggestions and edits before sending it off to YES' bassist Billy Sherwood, who recorded the vocals and put together the audio in just a few hours. Lastly, a local videographer, Thomas Stone, shot and edited the final video.

We think it turned out pretty good--let us know what you think! And remember to stay safe out there.

See you soon,

Alan White
Newcastle, Washington
21 April 2020

post_text: Sartori Elementary School kindergarten teacher Alisa Vinson Ames recently hosted a parade for her families and students. Sartori Elementary students attend the school from all over the district, which would make it difficult for school staff to plan any kind of a neighborhood parade, like we’ve seen with other schools. So, Alison instead had parents bring their students to a location near the school for 'car parade' that allowed everyone to see each other while practicing social distancing. Students and families were excited to physically see each other and their teachers for the first time in weeks.

post_text:
Congratulations to Talley High School teacher Stefeny Anderson who received two awards as the Veterans of Foreign Wars (VFW) History Teacher of the Year presented by Skyway VFW and VFW District #11. The award honors teachers who teach US and world history.

Stefeny, the granddaughter of a WWII Veteran, was selected based on her classroom approach to enlighten and inform her students about US history it’s connection to other nations and cultures. She empowers students to use their civic power, and diverse backgrounds and cultures, to be change makers in their communities. During the class study of Veterans Affairs in Contemporary World Problems, she has veterans visit her classroom and students send local veterans holiday cards and letters.

Stefeny’s mantra is “True patriotism is informed civic involvement.”

Responses by our Newcastle and Renton families and neighbors to the important 2020 Census continue to increase:
• Nearly 63% of Newcastle residents have responded
• Nearly 56% of Renton residents have responded

In comparison, in 2010, the last time the Census took place:
• a total of only 74% of Newcastle residents responded (meaning more than 25% did not); and
• just under 68% of Renton residents responded (nearly a third of residents did not
• only 73% of King County residents responded

Washington state will lose about $5.8 million over ten years for every 100 households missed in the count. Let's beat those numbers this year and commit to filling out the important 2020 Census which provides funding for hospitals, roads, school lunches, firefighters, families in need, more. Grab you form and fill out my2020census.gov

New: Child does not need to be present to pick-up meals: Renton School District continues to provide free meals to any child, ages 1-18, in the front lot of most schools. Meals are “grab and go” and are intended to be taken off campus or even picked up through car windows:

Child does not need to be present to pick-up meal
Meals are provided Monday-Friday, 11 a.m. – 12 p.m.
Pick-up meals in person (walk-up) or drive thru
Meals are free and no ID is required
Students/families can pick up meals at any school or location nearest them (you don’t have to go to your school)
Please pre-order your meals for your pick-up location: www.rentonschools.us/students-families

Meals are available at nearly every school and at the following locations:
Creston Point, 13445 Martin Luther King Jr. Way, Seattle
Green Tree/Park Hill, 6900 S 125th St, Seattle
Plum Tree Park, 200 SW 5th Pl, Renton
Royal Hills, 3000 Royal Hills Dr SE, Renton
Stonebrook, 12210 SE Petrovitsky Rd, Renton

Census Day is Today!
The Census is crucially important for determining so many things for our community, region, and state, from federal funding to representation in Congress.

In 2019 alone, Washington schools received billions of dollars in federal funding based on Census data, including:
• $242 million in Title I Grants
• $230 million in Special Education Grants
• $201 million for National School Lunch Program
• and much, much more.

Now, more than ever, your participation in the Census is important. Please find your mailer from the Census Bureau and use the number on the form to complete your 2020 Census today. https://my2020census.gov/

The process is simple and takes only 5 minutes. That 5 minutes means millions of dollars in federal and state funds for programs that matter to our students, families, and communities from roads to schools to police to hospitals (now, more than ever we see the importance of properly funding our hospitals).

Grab your mailer with your household number and fill out your Census 2020 form now: https://my2020census.gov/

The King County Regional Donations Connector is available online to link up individuals, businesses, non-profits, and others who have resources with those who need them during the COVID-19 pandemic.

The Donations Connector will help make sure services, supplies, and funding reach health care providers, first responders, and social service entities working on the front lines.

The website at kingcounty.gov/emergency/donate serves three major functions:

A system that allows donations and offers of assistance to be used in the response effort.

An online “marketplace” where offering organizations can be matched to those in need.

An easily searchable list of ways the public can get help.

More than 60 students from 20 regional high schools, including Renton schools, competed last month for top honors at this year’s SkillsUSA Washington Aerospace Assembler Competition held at Boeing’s Everett plant. The SkillsUSA event puts students to the test to highlight the assembly skills they have been developing in classrooms as part of the Core Plus Aerospace curriculum. Students also participate in mock interviews and resume reviews with an aim of preparing them for in-demand manufacturing jobs.

In alignment with information provided by the Governor and his staff, all Renton Schools are open on Thursday, March 12 (with the exception of Hazen High School).

This afternoon, Renton School District leadership joined a call with the Governor and superintendents in King, Pierce, and Snohomish counties to discuss our coordinated approach to combating COVID-19 coronavirus. During the meeting, superintendents were asked to prepare for a potential regional school closure that could last over a month. After this meeting, Superintendent Pattenaude also met with union leaders to brief them on this evolving situation.

We anticipate more direction from the Governor’s Office tomorrow. We will update our families and community as soon as we have information to share.

Students from Lindbergh and Renton high schools recently competed in the state Health Occupations Students of America (HOSA) healthcare skills conference. Hazen High School students were also scheduled to compete but were unable to attend due to closure of the school. Students showed off their skills and competencies in Health Science and Biomedical Science, and networking, public speaking, and human anatomy. The students also learned about careers in the healthcare industry.

Two Renton High students, Jacqueline Abrego and Kimberly Anaya, placed third in their EMT competition which qualifies them for the international competition in Houston this summer.

HOSA is an international career and technical student skills organization.

post_text:
Taxpayers through the Renton School District will benefit from the district’s solid financial management, excellent credit rating, and a favorable bond market. The district recently completed the first sale of school construction bonds which were overwhelmingly approved by voters in the school construction measure on the November 5 ballot. The district’s sound financial position permitted it to raise $125 million in construction funds while securing an historically low interest rate of 2.2%. The resources will be used to fund construction projects at schools across the district and to build a new elementary school. By law, this funding is to be used only for school construction projects, renovations and upgrades; it cannot be used in the general fund or as part of the work to balance the 2020-2021 budget.

Investors were attracted by the district’s very strong Aa1 credit rating from Moody’s Investors Service. Read more at www.rentonschools.us/departments/capital-projects/school-construction-bond-nov2019

post_text:
Renton School District received word late tonight from Public Health – Seattle & King County that they received a positive COVID-19 test result for a student at Hazen High School. The student is at home recovering. The student has no siblings.

While initially Public Health recommended that Hazen High remain open regardless of test results, they now recommending we close Hazen High School for the remainder of this week as they work to determine who, if anybody, came in contact with the ill student to ensure it is safe for students and staff to return to school.

We understand this guidance has changed and recognize the hardship this places on our students and families. Our top priority is to ensure the safety of our school community. School will be closed through the end of this week. Public Health will provide us with guidance for the following week.

We will provide more information as we work through this process with Public Heath and the CDC.

post_text: Students in classrooms throughout the district are using Science, Technology, Engineering and Mathematics (STEM) to learn how things they see every day actually work. Students are learning analytical skills to research, develop, plan and draw conclusions; they use science skills to break down systems into smaller parts, recognize cause and effect relationships, and defend opinions using facts; they use mathematics skills for calculations and measurements; and they use technical skills to troubleshoot the source of a problem. An example pictured is 3rd-graders at Sartori Elementary School learning to apply knowledge of balanced forces and magnetism to build character statues.

Renton Schools and the King County Library System offer a FREE screening of the film Resilience: The Biology of Stress & The Science of Hope, Thursday, March 5, 4-6 p.m., at the Renton IKEA Performing Arts Center (at Renton High) 400 South 2nd Street.

The film explores the impact of toxic stress and Adverse Childhood Experiences (ACEs) on individuals, including children, and how communities can collectively create resilience so children can thrive. The free screening and follow-up panel discussion is open to all community members, families, school staff, health providers, service providers, and all who want to help build resilience in our children and our community.

post_text: Renton Academy principal Travis Hall was a featured presenter at the recent Council for Exceptional Children Conference in Portland, Oregon. Travis, along with co-presenters Dr. Lori Lynass from Sound Supports and Dr. Jeffrey Sprague from the University of Oregon, presented work on the philosophical foundations of Restorative Practices and the unique role of alternative education settings. Restorative practices promote inclusiveness, relationship-building and problem-solving for conflict resolution. Travis’ presentation concluded with an exploration of the programming and data that has resulted from Renton Academy’s adoption of Restorative Practices in 2015. As a result, Renton Academy has been invited to the national conference in Chicago this fall to present as an exemplar school.

Lindbergh High School senior Priti Ahya and Hazen High School senior Arnav Thareja have been named as finalists in the National Merit Scholarship Program. These two talented students received the designation by demonstrating distinguished performance on the PSAT and a high potential for future academic accomplishment. The distinction places them among only 16,000 Finalists nationwide who made it to this level of the scholarship competition, representing less than one percent of all U.S. high school seniors.
Priti and Arnav are now in the running for one of the 7,500 scholarships worth more than $32 million through the National Merit Scholarship Program.

Priti plans to study computer science at either Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT) or the University of Washington. Arnav will study computer science and artificial intelligence at either Stanford University; University of California, Berkeley; or University of Washington.

This week, Moody’s Investors Service reaffirmed Renton School District’s underlying credit rating at Aa1. Moody’s also assigned an enhanced credit rating of Aaa which will benefit the district's upcoming sale of construction bonds, made possible thanks to overwhelming voter support of the Nov. 2019 school construction election measure. The rating places Renton Schools as one of the highest rated school districts in Washington.

In its press release, Moody’s noted “The Aa1 underlying rating reflects remarkably strong economic growth, a diversifying tax base, rising household incomes and strong demographic trends.” Moody’s also noted Renton’s “strong management team” and conservative approach to budgeting as critical to the financial stability of the district.

A strong underlying credit rating generally allows school districts favorable interest rates on bond sales to build and renovate schools, which translates into reduced borrowing costs for taxpayers.

The Lindbergh High School boys swim team took home the title at the South Puget Sound League (SPSL) 2A Championship swim/dive meet on Saturday, Feb. 8. The team scored 402.5 points. This is the third year in a row the team has taken home the title. All together the team took home seven league titles from Saturday’s meet.
Lindbergh had a successful dual meet season with a record of 16-0 overall. This weekend the team will compete in the Central District Swim/Dive meet. (Story and photo courtesy of Renton Reporter)

A group of education leaders from the country of Georgia recently visited the region to connect with educators, programs, and organizations as they work to improve teacher recruitment and retention in their country. The group visited with Carla Smith to learn about our district’s Renton Teacher Academy program which works to strengthen the pathway from high school to teaching by recruiting high school students to become teachers in hard-to-fill positions.

The delegates, many of whom work in teacher training and professional development programs, are part of the World Affairs Council and the U.S. State Department's premier professional exchange program, the International Visitor Leadership Program.

Want to have a great time while also supporting our district high school seniors?

Join the Renton PTA Council for their annual Founders Day Dinner & Auction, Friday, March 27, 5:30 p.m. at the Maplewood Golf Course, 4050 Maple Valley Hwy, Renton.

Each year our PTA Council, the governing body for all of our district PTAs, celebrates the year’s success while raising funds for scholarships for Renton School District students. Tickets are just $40/per person and includes dinner, drinks, and an auction.

It’s a wonderful event for a great cause; and your money goes to support our students’ future!

Can’t make the event? Consider donating to the PTA Council scholarship fund online to support our graduating seniors at www.rentonptacouncil.org.

Renton School Board members are seeking nominations for the annual Outstanding Employee Awards. Each year our Board recognizes the hard work and dedication of district staff through the award in four categories:
• Outstanding Elementary Teacher
• Outstanding Secondary (middle/high school) Teacher
• Outstanding Building Support Person
• Outstanding District Support Person
This is an excellent opportunity to recognize a teacher and support staff member who demonstrate high levels of job performance, dedication and support for students, coworkers, parents and community.

The online nomination process is simple. Be sure to complete each box (the more complete the entry form, the better chances that your nominee will be selected). Deadline for nominations is Friday, Feb. 14.

Recipients will be honored at the March 11 School Board meeting.

Nominate a deserving staff member today: https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSecbBblnoPBenUoSnLUdqFyfN53T4piIwO_hdOK2YOs1z8a_w/viewform

Due to rising rivers, mud slides and standing water, the City of Renton has closed two of the three westbound lanes on Maple Valley Highway (just a few yards east of I-405) for an indefinite time period. That closure will greatly impact some school bus routes for Lindbergh High, McKnight and Nelsen Middle School, and Sartori, Talbot Hill, and Tiffany Park elementary schools as students head home after school today.

There is no change to the school day or after school activities. We anticipate many other school bus routes will also be impacted as roadways are altered due to rain.

Our school bus drivers will work quickly and safely to get students home at the end of the day. But families are asked to be patient as our school buses are impacted by weather, traffic, and road conditions.

Students in Jordan Larsen’s Family and Consumer Science class at Dimmitt Middle School are learning life lessons that will stay with them well into their adult years. The 7th- and 8th-graders are learning to manage personal finance, and how to cook and sew.

During the sewing unit students are learning to hand stitch so they can fix a rip in their clothes, sew on a button, and make other repairs. Students also learn how to use a sewing machine by sewing pillows they later take home and use themselves or give as gifts, and even for their pets.

Students love the chance to work with their hands and getting to know how the machines work. And while sewing has been fun, students are getting excited to start cooking again.

Highlands Elementary School was recently selected by Amazon as the site to announce its donation of $2 million to support STEM education programs. Amazon’s Future Engineer program will make the donation to two Seattle-based nonprofits with the aim of helping a more diverse group of students find work in science and technology.

The Pacific Science Center will get $1 million to invest in its flagship Science on Wheels program, which brings traveling workshops, exhibits and live stage shows to students throughout the state.

Washington STEM, a Seattle-based advocate for diversity in tech and the sciences, will use its money to help more students from low-income and rural communities as well as students of color and girls and young women gain access to tech education.

By 2030, 70 percent of all family-wage Washington jobs will require education beyond high school, including certificates and apprenticeships. Two-thirds of those jobs will require STEM skills.

Read more at the Renton Reporter linked below.

post_text:
Renton High School senior Faith Richardson has plans to one day be superintendent of schools. Recently she joined Superintendent Damien Pattenaude as Superintendent for a Day to learn more about the education and business side of managing a large school district. She also had conversations with students and staff, and ask questions about education, college, business and other topics.

Faith is quick to share that her father, Rich, is the person most responsible for her many successes. But she says that the professionalism and compassion shown to her by teachers and school staff throughout Renton Schools helped shape her love of learning and her desire to become involved as a school leader.

Faith is enrolled in Renton High's International Baccalaureate program; she’s a poet; and holds the Washington State record in the 100-meter dash. After graduation, Faith will enroll University of Massachusetts with a track & field scholarship and major in English, minor in psychology, on her way to one day lead a school district.

Renton Schools is helping more students be financially prepared for college. With hard work by school staff, 90% of the district’s eligible middle school students have signed up for the state’s College Bound Scholarship program, which, in combination with other state aid, will cover tuition at state public college rates. Eligible students must sign-up in middle school, by June 30 of their 8th-grade year, to receive this early commitment of state funding. Students who sign-up for the scholarship graduate from high school and enroll in college at higher rates than their peers. Washington Governor Jay Inslee has recognized Renton Schools with the Gold Star Award as one of the state’s top school districts that exceeded the state average to ensure families are signed up for the state college funding opportunity.

Renton Schools is helping more students be financially prepared for college. Eligible students must sign-up in middle school, by June 30 of their 8th-grade year, to receive this early commitment of state funding. Students who sign-up for the scholarship graduate from high school and enroll in college at higher rates than their peers. Washington Governor Jay Inslee has recognized Renton Schools with the Gold Star Award as one of the state’s top school districts that exceeded the state average to ensure families are signed up for the state college funding opportunity.
The College Bound Scholarship Program is administered by the Washington Student Achievement Council. Students and families can learn more and apply at https://wsac.wa.gov/pathways.

A dangerous new challenge that is making its way across social media is causing harm to youth and damage to homes. The challenge implores kids to record a video of themselves partially plugging in a cell phone charger into a wall socket and then sliding a penny between the charger and the wall, then post the results on TikTok.

Placing the penny across an active electrical connection will create sparks that can damage the outlet, start a house fire and injure the person.

Families are asked to warn their children of this dangerous challenge.

Hazen High School senior Luis Hernandez is a world-class photographer, whose photos are included in an international art exhibit in Barcelona, Spain.

That’s pretty impressive given that Luis only began taking photos while in a high school photography class during his junior year. Luis says he loves the ability to tell stories through art and photography. So, he bought a camera, started taking his craft seriously, and even signed up for journalism classes at Hazen High to hone his writing and story-telling abilities.

Luis recently submitted photos for an exhibit, along with more than 57,000 other entries from photographers around the globe. More than 145 million people around the world voted for the winning photographs. Luis’ photos made the cut and will be displayed Feb. 14-16 in the GuruShots International Art exhibit in the Valid World Hall in Barcelona, Spain.

Luis says he’s decided on his career path to become a photojournalist and find stories to tell all over the world.

As part of her “Remarkable American Women” class, H.O.M.E. Program student Danika Bendickson created a presentation about Seattle Police Chief Carmen Best, the first African American woman to hold the position. Danika met Chief Best over the holidays at a Seattle Police Dept. function (Danika’s father is a Seattle police officer) and invited her to speak to the class. Chief Best agreed and recently visited with students at our H.O.M.E. program.

Messages Chief Best shared with students included:
• Treat people right. Treat them as you’d like to be treated.
• Surround yourself with the right friends.
• Always have a passion for learning.
• Jot down your thoughts/dreams and set goals. Pursue them.
• Be willing to serve people.
• Persevere through the bad days and enjoy the good days.
• If someone gives you an opportunity, take it. They wouldn’t offer it if they didn’t believe in you.

Lindbergh High School’s cross-country coach Jef Rettmann was inducted into the Washington State Track & Field Coaches Associations (WSTFCA) Hall of Fame this weekend during a special banquet in Tacoma.

Jef (left in photo) has been a coach and teacher at Lindbergh High for two decades. During his career, Jef ’s boys and girls teams have won 22 League Championships; his boys team won the 2011 2A Boys State Championship; he’s had five teams place in the top four at State; and he’s coached individual state champions Sam Ahlbeck and Sarah Reiter. In 2011 Jef was named State Coach of the Year; in 2016, he was named the South Puget Sound League's Coach of the Year.

Jef attended Mead High School in Spokane where he participated in track, cross country, and basketball. He now joins his high school track coach Pat Tyson in the WSCCCA Hall of Fame.

Public Health Seattle & King County is offering a free vaccination clinic on Thursday, Jan. 23, 3-8 p.m. at Federal Way High School, 30611 16th Ave S, Federal Way.

The clinic is open to all King County K-12 students, up to age 18 (students under 18 must be accompanied by a parent/guardian or bring a signed consent form). If available, bring student vaccination records with you. No appointment needed.

The clinic offers all vaccines required for school and more, while supplies last:
• Dtap/Tdap (Tetanus, Diphtheria & Pertussis)
• Hepatitis B
• HPV (Human Papillomavirus)
• Influenza (flu)
• IPV (Polio)
• MMR (Measles, Mumps, Rubella)
• Meningococcal
• Varicella (Chickenpox)

For more information and to print a consent form: https://kingcounty.gov/depts/health/communicable-diseases/immunization/child/free-vaccine-clinic.aspx

Meadow Crest Early Learning Center is closed; there is no out-of-district transportation; and no zero-hour classes.

School buses will run on Limited Transportation Routes:
https://www.rentonschools.us/departments/support-services/transportation/inclement-weather-limited-transportation-routes

All staff are expected at their work place as close to regular work hours as safely possible.

La escuela Meadow Crest Centro de temprana edad no tiene escuela hoy. No hay transportación fuera del distrito y no hay clases del cero periodo.

Los autobuses escolares andan en rutas limitadas: https://www.rentonschools.us/departments/support-services/transportation/inclement-weather-limited-transportation-routes

post_text: Lakeridge Elementary School support staff have been recognized as Sound Discipline Champions for their work to build relationships with students. post_text:
Renton School District serves thousands of students and families who speak both English and their home language. In our classrooms, this means recognizing a student’s home language as an asset to learning.

Since 2016, more than 130 of our high school students who possess a high level of proficiency in speaking, reading, and writing in one or more world languages in addition to English have earned a Seal of Biliteracy on their high school diploma and high school transcripts.

Our students have earned Seal of Biliteracy in a dozen languages including Chinese, Ilocanos, Korean, Lao, Punjabi, Romanian, Russian, Spanish, Turkish, Twi, Ukrainian, and Vietnamese.

post_text: Thanks to voter support of our Technology Levies, we’re providing our teachers with high-level teaching technology like Promethean ActivPanels which replace classroom projectors and other bulky devices. Teachers can connect their laptops to the panels to share curriculum content; they can write on the screen like a whiteboard using a stylus or even their fingers, erase the screen with their palm, and save their work from the screen directly to files; they can pinch and zoom content on the screen like a laptop screen, and much more. The multi-use technology allows teachers to move freely around a classroom and interact with student devices, increasing student collaboration and participation.

post_text:
A generous group of local citizens and organizations who support education recently provided cash grants totaling more than $40,000 to teachers throughout the district for use in classrooms and schools to improve student learning. Through the annual Community Giving (Circle of Giving) campaign, teachers applied for grants for up $1,000 for materials and items they feel can help expand their work in the classroom.

Classroom grants were provided for science, music, art, literature, drama, and even specialized clubs and activities like material for an after-school knitting club and field trips to regional cultural events.

The grants were provided by Renton Schools Foundation, Joy Poff Fund for Education and Families, Harper Engineering Children’s Need Fund, and Renton Regional Community Foundation. Representatives from the funding organizations said applications submitted by district staff “reflected the intellectual curiosity, dedication, and commitment of the professionals working in the Renton School District.”

http://rentonschoolsfoundation.org/
http://www.rentonfoundation.org/

There's talk of possible snow in our area in the coming days and weeks, which could lead to school delays or closures.

If inclement weather-like snow or ice-makes a school schedule change necessary, the decision will be made by the Superintendent and communicated to families and staff by:
• Phone call/email/text to all families and staff (please ensure your school has your updated phone/email)
• Renton School District website and school websites
• The district's Facebook page
• The district's Twitter page
• The district's Instagram
• Local media outlets (TV, radio)

If road conditions warrant, we may also change some of our school bus routes and pick-up/drop-off locations. See your limited school bus route here: www.rentonschools.us/departments/support-services/transportation/inclement-weather-limited-transportation-routes.

Learn more about what happens if bad weather causes school delays or closures, and expectations for students and staff, at this website: www.rentonschools.us/departments/community-relations/inclementweather.

High school students throughout Renton Schools are gaining hands-on knowledge and skills, along with industry certification in high-demand fields. An industry certification is a credential recognized by business and industry at the local, state or national level, because it measures competency and validates the knowledge base and skills that show mastery in an industry.
Renton School students are earning industry certifications in business and marketing, computer science, family and consumer science, healthcare and emergency services and more. Learn more at www.rentonschools.us/learning-and-teaching/career-and-technical-education/cte-in-the-renton-school-district/career-connected-learning/industry-certification

Thanks to your support, Renton Schools Foundation has had a successful year supporting student learning in schools throughout the district.

Through contributions from individuals and businesses, Renton Schools Foundation has provided funding to allow more students to participate in Science, Engineering, Technology and Math (STEM) activities; provided more than $23,000 to music programs; and will soon provide teachers with $25,000 in grants for classroom projects. Additionally, in partnership with Renton Rotary, the Foundation will pilot GoBabyGo, a project to help children with mobility issues.

Your ongoing caring and support is having a big impact. Let’s continue this work together to help move our schools forward in positive ways. Learn more: www.rentonschoolsfoundation.org

Renton High School senior Jeric Liam learned a lot about himself through Renton High's hands-on learning and manufacturing classes, Core Plus Aerospace. Not only did he learn valuable work skills that will help him get a high-paying job, he also learned about work ethics, leadership and perseverance: life-skills that have helped him work with other students in activities like yearbook, wrestling, and others.

The Core Plus Aerospace and AJAC Aerospace Joint Apprenticeship Committee program is offered at all Renton School District comprehensive high schools, and is one of many classes provided to students to ensure they graduate with many options for a successful future.

Read Jeric's story in the Renton Reporter: www.rentonreporter.com/marketplace/core-plus-aerospace-gives-me-the-experiences-and-skills-to-succeed

Renton School District continues work to keep students and staff safe at school. Thanks to continued voter support of school building construction measures (like the one passed on Nov. 5 by more than 70% of voters) we’re building schools that are resilient to hazards like earthquakes and other disasters.

We’re also working with the King County Office of Emergency Management to further reduce risk and, in case of earthquake, flooding, severe weather, public health emergencies and other hazards, have our school community eligible for federal grant funding for hazard mitigation projects from FEMA. Your input in this planning process will be used to prioritize hazard mitigation investments by helping us identify and weigh critical values. Want to get involved, or have questions? Please visit our Hazard Mitigation website (plan available on Dec. 20. 2019) or email Hazard.Mitigation.District@rentonschools.us.

post_text:
There's still time to catch a great play by the wonderful Hazen High School Players:
Up the Down Staircase
Dec. 13 & 14 at 7 p.m.
Matinee performance Dec. 14 at 1 p.m.
Hazen High Auditorium, 1101 Hoquiam Ave NE, Renton
Ticket are $7/$9 at the door

Set in the late 1960s, the play revolves around Sylvia Barrett, an idealistic English teacher at an inner-city high school who hopes to nurture her students' interest in classic literature. post_text: Renton School District’s special education advisory team met recently to continue their work to improve classroom instruction for all students. A 30-member team consisting of special education teachers, psychologists and therapists, along with principals and assistant principals also brought along classroom teachers from their school to work with the group to review student data, identify barriers to inclusive practices, and ways all staff can remove barriers to student learning. The team will continue to work throughout the school year to create a multi-faceted, multi-year action plan to improve student outcomes.

Renton School District students can gain college credit for high school classwork. Students who complete specific classes can earn college credits to be used at Renton Technical College, Highline College and Pima Medical Institute. Some examples of these high school classes are accounting, anatomy & physiology, computer aided drafting, financial algebra, macroeconomics (AP), medical terminology, website design, and others. The district worked with the local colleges to ensure high school courses aligned with college requirements as part of our work to connect high school learning directly to real-world experience and provide students with many options after high school graduation.

Students and families can find out more about how to be college and career ready after high school graduation at the district’s Career and Technical Education website www.rentonschools.us/learning-and-teaching/career-and-technical-education

Thanks to voter support in School Construction ballot measures, Renton School District continues to improve safety and security by upgrading and installing additional high-definition cameras and recording devices in schools throughout the district.

Along with our safety and security practices, and the support of our school and district security professionals and Renton police officers assigned as School Resources Officers, the additional cameras will help ensure that all schools and grounds can be monitored consistently and effectively. Installation of cameras will help to monitor hallways, entrances, and school grounds; deter crime or bullying; discourage vandalism and trespassing; and greatly aid in gathering information in the event of an incident.

While we’ve had cameras in middle and high schools, these new cameras offer much improved video and images and will be installed at all schools to provide equity throughout the district.

Two Lindbergh High School students were selected for the Youth Production Technician apprentice program at HYDRO Systems USA in partnership with Aerospace Joint Apprenticeship Committee (AJAC). Andrey Grushke and Prescott Schwartz will work in the 2-year paid apprenticeship which takes students through bench work, inspection and machining basics along with college-level courses to develop career-ready skills in the aerospace/manufacturing industry. The program also provides students with college credits.

HYDRO Systems USA, based in Kent, Wash., is an industry leader in providing aerospace ground support equipment and airframe and engine maintenance tooling supports for the aviation industry. The apprenticeship program works to develop and grow a talent pipeline for an industry in current shortage of skilled workers. The partnership is another example of Renton School District’s work to provide students with many options after high school graduation.

post_text: Bryn Mawr Elementary School teachers are spending this Teacher Training Day continuing their evaluation of individual and systemic practices that are inequitable to students of color. Staff continue their learning journey about issues of equity in education, anchoring their work in Zaretta Hammond’s “Culturally Responsive Teaching and the Brain.” Bryn Mawr teacher-leaders led colleagues through a data carousel where they analyzed current student behavior data broken down by ethnicity and behavior, diving deeply into what the data says about how student behavior is being address and how to dismantle the inequities within practices at school.

Hazen High School’s annual Holiday Gala Concert is Thursday, Dec. 19, 7 p.m. at the Hazen High auditorium, 1101 Hoquiam Ave SE, Renton. The event is the one night a year that Hazen’s award-winning music programs come together for a holiday concert, including the Symphonic Band, Philharmonic Orchestra, Vox Lumini, and Chamber Chorus, under the direction Chris Coy and Josh Viles. Families, players and staff were grateful for the support they received from Renton School District staff at the event, and they were impressed with Renton Stadium facilities.

We're thankful to our voters who approve our school construction measures to allow us to renovate and maintain our schools and the stadium in top operating condition, and we’re glad to have such a great facility to support other local school districts.

post_text:
Congratulations to the Seattle Sounders for winning the MLS Cup today 3-1 over Toronto to become champions of Major League Soccer.

Here’s some interesting history of the Sounders connected to Renton School District.

In 2006, as Sounders club's majority owner Adrian Hanauer was working to create a major league soccer team in the Seattle area, he approached Renton School District administration to discuss leasing Renton Stadium to become the home for the new major league team. The proposal included taking out the track at the stadium to expand the field to MLS league standards. It would’ve also meant having our high schools sports teams play games elsewhere during the major league soccer season. Renton School District could not agree to the requirements.

Sounders owners continued to work to become a solid national franchise big enough to play at CentryLink Field, and now, national champions.

https://www.soundersfc.com

post_text: Congratulations to Renton Technical College for being named one of top community colleges in the country by The Aspen Institute College Excellence Program. RTC was selected from a pool of nearly 1,000 public two-year colleges nationwide, and was recognized for its strength and improvement in student outcomes – including learning, completion rates, employment rates and earnings, and equity. RTC boasts a completion rate of 65%– the highest in the state and among the highest in the country – and a job placement rate of 85%. RTC was also named as a top 10 Aspen Prize college in 2015. As a finalist, RTC is eligible to compete for the $1 million Aspen Prize for Community College Excellence, the nation’s signature recognition of high achievement and performance. https://www.rtc.edu/aspen-2021

Mail your ballot at any mailbox (no stamp needed) or place it in a King County Election ballot drop box. Find one near you: www.kingcounty.gov/depts/elections/how-to-vote/ballots/returning-my-ballot/ballot-drop-boxes.aspx

KINGCOUNTY.GOV
King County Elections

post_text: Talley High School student Isaiah Mawudeku was selected as a Transformational Student Leader for the state of Washington. Isaiah was selected for making a lasting, transformational change in his community; specifically his volunteer work with the Seattle Juvenile Courts as a mediation specialist. Isaiah believes in restorative justice for youth facing incarceration, and is working to try to ensure that students, especially students of color, are given opportunities to learn from their mistakes. Isaiah and his family attended a banquet at the Museum of History and Industry, where he gave an acceptance speech to a crowd of over 300 in attendance.

¡Recuerde votar!
Estamos a menos de una semana de la fecha límite de las elecciones (las boletas deben llegar a las Elecciones del Condado de King o enviarse por correo antes de este martes 5 de noviembre).
La medida de construcción escolar del Distrito Escolar de Renton debe alcanzar dos objetivos importantes para tener éxito:
1. un mínimo de 18,578 boletas devueltas
2. un mínimo de 60% aprobado
Actualmente tenemos 8.194 boletas devueltas (solo el 44% del número necesario). Asegúrese que escuchen su voz. Envíe su boleta por correo ahora (no necesita sello).
Obtenga más información sobre la medida de Construcción de Escuelas en el sito web; https://www.rentonschools.us/our-district/school-construction-bond-nov2019

post_text:
Dimmitt Middle School students have a great new after-school program that provides them with hands-on learning opportunities as they rebuild and repair bicycles. The program, offered by Wheellab, inspires students to think creatively and develop essential life skills, fine motor skills, and problem-solving skills while also learning to be safe, conscientious bike riders.

WheelLab owner Lance Latimer (who’s wife Stephanie is a teacher at Bryn Mawr Elementary) created the company to help students learn skills they can use for a lifetime. Lance takes old, seemingly run-down bicycles and helps students turn them back into usable, fun transportation. Students get to keep their bike project after the 8-week course which is taught in the back of WheelLab’s mobile trailer. www.wheellab.org/

Remember to Vote!

We're less than a week away from the election deadline (ballots must arrive at King County Elections or be postmarked by this Tuesday, Nov. 5).

Renton School District's School Construction measure must reach two important targets to be successful:
1. a minimum of 18,578 ballots returned
2. a minimum of 60% Approved

We are currently at 8,194 ballots returned (only 44% of the needed number). Make sure your voice is heard. Mail your ballot now (no stamp needed).

www.rentonschools.us/our-district/school-construction-bond-nov2019

post_text:
Last Saturday, Renton School Board members along with Superintendent Dr. Damien Pattenaude and Renton Mayor Denis Law joined former Seattle Seahawks receiver Doug Baldwin in cutting the ribbon for the new Family First Community Center, to be built at Cascade Elementary School in 2020.

In 2016, Renton School Board members began work with Baldwin and the City of Renton, WA -- Government in a partnership to build Baldwin's Family First Community Center in the Cascade/Benson neighborhood. Our Board approved a lease of 17,000 square feet of land next to Cascade Elementary School for the project. Baldwin has worked since then to raise the needed funding for the project which includes a vision to provide youth and families in the area with a community center that offers health, fitness, educational and recreational opportunities.
Learn more at https://rentonwa.gov/city_hall/mayor/family_first_community_center

post_text: Renton Rotary is again providing every 3rd grade student in the district with a personal children's dictionary. For more than a decade, Rotarians have provided district students with a dictionary they can take home to read, learn new words and facts, use for homework, and in some cases help improve the English language skills of siblings and family members. Rotary members will spend the next two weeks visiting elementary schools to personally deliver more than 1,200 dictionaries to students.

King County Elections reports that in the Aug. 2019 primary election nearly 7,800 voters did not have their voice heard:

• 1,616 ballots were rejected because signatures didn’t match
• 554 ballots were rejected because they were not signed
• 5,625 arrived too late to be counted

Democracy is important; voting is an important right. Make sure your vote counts in the Nov. 5, 2019 Election.
• Turn your ballot over (Renton School District’s School Construction measure is on the back)
• Sign your ballot
• Mail your ballot immediately (no stamp needed)

Vote by Nov. 5!

post_text:
Congratulations to Hazen High School girls swim team who competed in leagues over the weekend. The team had several top six finishes and several athletes beat their own personal record. All three relay teams and several individual swimmers will move to districts this week.

Reminder: the measure on your election ballot includes a needed complete overhaul and renovation of Hazen High pool. Remember to mail your ballot by Nov. 5! www.rentonschools.us/our-district/school-construction-bond-nov2019
